The biggest mistake I made wasn't moving too slowly. It was leaving shelves empty while I chased new upgrades. Customers walked in, couldn't find what they wanted, and left before I earned a coin. After a few runs, I realized a busy store only makes money when products are always available.

Monkey Mart looks simple, but every task is connected. You harvest crops, refill displays, collect payments, unlock new stations, and manage workers at the same time. Ignoring one job for too long creates a chain reaction that slows the entire supermarket.

Now I never rush to expand. I wait until my current section runs smoothly before opening another. A smaller store with full shelves usually earns more than a larger one that's constantly running out of stock.

That's why Monkey Mart stays fun even after many playthroughs. You're not just growing a supermarket. You're learning how to spot problems, fix them quickly, and keep everything running without wasting a single trip across the store.
Try now at https://monkeymart6x.io
